[3] Scab disease - USA (Michigan, Indiana): new strains
Date: Wed 13 Jul 2011
Source: FreshPlaza, UPI (United Press International) report [edited]
http://www.freshplaza.com/news_detail.asp?id=83364


Apple disease proving resistant to attack
-----------------------------------------
US orchard growers are discovering some commonly used fungicides are
no longer effective at controlling a damaging apple scourge. Janna
Beckerman, Purdue University, said extensive long-term use of 4
popular fungicides has led to apple scab resistances in apples in
Indiana and Michigan. Apple scab is highly destructive.

"But the most disturbing thing we found is that many of the samples
we tested were resistant to all 4 fungicides. This is full-blown
resistance. It can cause orchard failures," Beckerman said. "A grower,
depending on the amount of diversity in the orchard, could lose the
entire crop."

The only option is to use older fungicides that are tightly
regulated, require more frequent application, and are more expensive.
"It's going to change how growers manage their orchards," she said.
"The more susceptible apple cultivars, like McIntosh, will become more
chemically intensive to manage. Growers have few options as it is, and
this will limit their options even further."

